incial trade. This economic vision remains a vital part of Canada’s constitutional order and is relevant to a purposive interpretation of the Constitution. But contemporary legal discourse has begun to lose touch with this vision, with regrettable consequences in a number of different policy areas.Exploring the implications of the economic Constitution in the context of contemporary issues – including disputes over interprovincial trade and jurisdictional tensions between federal, provincial, and Indigenous governments with respect to the environment and the economy – Trade and Commerce restores economic ideas to the forefront of constitutional thinking in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNon-tariff trade barrierszCanadaxProvinces. 0aTrade regulationzCanadaxProvinces. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  a1867.  aAboriginal.  aCharlottetown.  aConference.  aIndigenous.  aJohn Macdonald.  aParliament.  aPeace.  aQuebec.  aautonomy.  acentralization.  acivil.  aconstitutional.  adecentralization.  adiversity.  adivision.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  afederal.  afederalism.  afree.  agood.  agovernment.  ahistory.  aintegration.  ainternal.  ainterpretation.  ainterprovincial.  alaw.  alegal.  alegislature.  alocal.  anatural.  aorder.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apowers.  aproperty.  aprovince.  aprovincial.  apurpose.  apurposive.  aresources.  arights.  aself-government.  asubsidiarity.  atheory.  aunity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228016472?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyt